ce:section.ce:para:
Among TMDCs family, molybdenum disulphide (MoS2) has been the most explored because of its direct bandgap and high electron mobility. Although 2-D MoS2 has been known for its absorption in visible and NIR regions, there is a need to extend the absorption region in UV. Therefore, the combination of MoS2 with CDs which absorb in the UV region broadens the absorbance range. As a consequence the CDs/MoS2 could be utilized in broadband photodetectors, as it was proposed by Sahatiya et al. [170]. More specifically, they fabricated a flexible broadband CQDs/MoS2 photodetector on cellulose paper, where its response under UV illumination was due to CQDs, while under visible and NIR illumination was because of MoS2. The synthesis of CQDs was performed by a pyrolytic treatment of chia seeds, while the growth of MoS2 nanosheets was performed by a one-step hydrothermal method, using a solution of sodium molybdate (Na2MoO4·2H2O) and thiourea. Finally, the CQDs/MoS2 photodetector was fabricated by masking MoS2-cellulose paper on two ends using Al followed by drop casting of CQDs solution. The schematic of the fabrication process is shown in Fig. 15
                        . The distribution of CQDs on MoS2 not only broadens the absorption range, but also forms unipolar junctions which create a small electric field; thereby assisting photogenerated electron-hole separation. The behavior of CQDs/MoS2 photodetector under different light illumination was evaluated based on I-V studies (Fig. 16
                        ). In all cases, current was increased with increasing intensity, which could be attributed to the improved number of photogenerated electron-hole pairs. In a similar study, Liu et al. [171] present their work on a CQDs/MoS2 photodetector, with higher photoresponsivity and detectivity than MoS2. Furthermore, in a recent study by Majd et al. [172], the fabrication of a CDs/MoS2 transistor and its applications as a Hg2+ aptasensor are reported.
